Goodness, already?

243
00:24:22,920 --> 00:24:26,163
Where are the fireworks?
-Strange.

244
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:56,162
I know a nice game.

245
00:24:56,680 --> 00:24:59,365
We have to pretend that we
don't know each other.

246
00:25:00,600 --> 00:25:05,686
Yes! Hello, sir.
I don't know you.

247
00:25:06,520 --> 00:25:08,648
I don't know you either.
-My name's Abel.

248
00:25:08,840 --> 00:25:10,763
What a coincidence, so's mine.

249
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:12,729
That's impossible, you're Victor.

250
00:25:12,920 --> 00:25:14,490
Isn't it too confusing if you're
called Abel as well?

251
00:25:14,680 --> 00:25:17,889
But I think it's silly
if you're called Abel as well.

252
00:25:18,080 --> 00:25:19,525
Yes, it's silly.

253
00:25:19,720 --> 00:25:21,529
Why not Fred, or Harry.

254
00:25:21,720 --> 00:25:23,722
Right, Harry then.

255
00:25:23,920 --> 00:25:28,847
I say Harry, are you married?
-Certainly. To a very stupid woman.

256
00:25:29,040 --> 00:25:31,202
I'm not stupid.

257
00:25:33,440 --> 00:25:36,125
Who is that lady?
-I don't know her.

258
00:25:36,360 --> 00:25:37,691
I'd like to introduce myself.

259
00:25:37,880 --> 00:25:39,689
I'd rather you didn't.

260
00:25:39,880 --> 00:25:43,282
I'd rather she didn't either.
-I'm playing as well, you know.

261
00:25:43,480 --> 00:25:46,962
Hey, Dove. It's only a game, isn't it?
-Yes, between the three of us!

262
00:25:47,160 --> 00:25:48,969
You're playing too, aren't you?

263
00:25:49,160 --> 00:25:50,491
Not if I can introduce myself.

264
00:25:50,680 --> 00:25:53,445
But that's the game.
You've got to butt in.

265
00:25:53,640 --> 00:25:56,484
I say, Abel, I've got two tickets
for the horse-races.

266
00:25:56,680 --> 00:25:57,727
Do you feel like coming?

267
00:25:57,920 --> 00:26:01,766
Yes, I'd like that.
-Can I ask you something?

268
00:26:02,840 --> 00:26:05,047
Did you hear something?
-No, I didn't hear a thing.

269
00:26:05,440 --> 00:26:08,330
What's this? How can I butt in then?

270
00:26:08,600 --> 00:26:09,886
I just heard it again.

271
00:26:10,200 --> 00:26:12,282
I heard something as well this time.

272
00:26:15,640 --> 00:26:16,766
Why are you stopping?

273
00:27:33,680 --> 00:27:37,844
Victor was walking on the other side
of the street. He crossed over.

274
00:27:48,400 --> 00:27:51,563
And I saw him but he didn't strike.

275
00:27:52,120 --> 00:27:54,202
And suddenly he was standing
in front of me.

276
00:27:54,800 --> 00:27:58,771
And he said: "Would you like
to have a drink with me?"

277
00:27:58,960 --> 00:28:02,601
I hesitated, after all
he was a stranger.

278
00:28:02,920 --> 00:28:05,764
Then he did something which...

279
00:28:07,200 --> 00:28:10,522
...it threw me right off guard.
-What did he do then?

280
00:28:10,720 --> 00:28:12,006
He looked at me...

281
00:28:12,320 --> 00:28:16,006
...a bit severely actually...

282
00:28:16,720 --> 00:28:19,963
...and he raised his hand to my head.

283
00:28:20,360 --> 00:28:22,647
It made me jump a bit.

284
00:28:23,360 --> 00:28:26,443
He stroked a lock of hair
out of my eyes...

285
00:28:26,640 --> 00:28:29,803
...like that... behind my ear.

286
00:28:39,320 --> 00:28:45,441
That's the way to do it,
very gently.

287
00:28:52,760 --> 00:28:55,331
Abel doesn't even know what
a negro is, just to name one thing.

288
00:28:55,520 --> 00:28:58,649
Everyone knows what a negro is.

289
00:28:59,720 --> 00:29:02,246
Even so, a television wouldn't
do him any harm.

290
00:29:02,440 --> 00:29:04,886
Television is a load of nonsense.

291
00:29:05,080 --> 00:29:09,802
Strange men and women
laughing at you.

292
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:12,890
They can't even see you.
"So nice to have you with us again."

293
00:29:13,080 --> 00:29:16,801
Ridiculous!
I'm not there...

294
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:19,765
...you're not either,
and neither is Abel.

295
00:29:20,560 --> 00:29:22,005
What about a nice film?

296
00:29:22,200 --> 00:29:24,362
Now, that's an even bigger
load of rubbish.

297
00:29:24,560 --> 00:29:28,770
Take a cowboy film. This cowboy,
hasn't he got any parents...

298
00:29:28,960 --> 00:29:29,882
...whom he visits from
time to time?

299
00:29:30,080 --> 00:29:33,323
Or have those parents died?
Is this cowboy a foundling?

300
00:29:33,520 --> 00:29:34,931
Has he got brothers and sisters?

301
00:29:35,120 --> 00:29:37,282
Has he had an education?

302
00:29:37,480 --> 00:29:39,687
Not a word about that, no.

303
00:29:39,880 --> 00:29:43,248
If you're on stage you don't
say to the audience:

304
00:29:43,440 --> 00:29:46,603
"I'm so-and-so, I went
to grammar school...

305
00:29:46,800 --> 00:29:47,801
...and I've got two brothers."

306
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:50,287
Of course not. But it comes up
in that piece.

307
00:29:50,480 --> 00:29:52,881
I play an Earl,
who's fallen on hard times...

308
00:29:53,080 --> 00:29:55,208
...and I say to the person
playing the opposite me...

309
00:29:55,400 --> 00:29:59,007
Christine, yes, that I have studied.

310
00:30:00,200 --> 00:30:03,921
The detective you played last year
never mentioned his education.

311
00:30:04,120 --> 00:30:06,043
That was a rotten play.

312
00:30:29,520 --> 00:30:30,806
First I want the kitchen painted.

313
00:31:51,240 --> 00:31:54,084
You shake hands with her
and introduce yourself.

314
00:31:55,360 --> 00:31:57,966
Don't squeeze! Normal.

315
00:32:00,480 --> 00:32:04,166
Not like a damp sponge.
Normal, a normal handshake.

316
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:09,081
Hello, I'm Abel.

317
00:32:09,280 --> 00:32:10,691
You see, there's nothing to it.

318
00:32:13,360 --> 00:32:16,091
And then you say something.
-This evening, I will.

319
00:32:16,280 --> 00:32:17,850
This evening, my foot! Now!

320
00:32:18,040 --> 00:32:19,451
I could say anything.
It depends on her as well.

321
00:32:19,640 --> 00:32:22,325
Nothing depends on her.
It depends on you.

322
00:32:22,600 --> 00:32:24,807
She's unsure of herself,
you have to put her at ease.

323
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:26,331
She could be the first to say
something as well?

324
00:32:26,520 --> 00:32:27,965
She won't be the first!

325
00:32:28,160 --> 00:32:29,844
How do you know?
-That's how it goes.

326
00:32:30,040 --> 00:32:34,921
The man speaks, and the woman
replies... now and then. And then...

327
00:32:35,400 --> 00:32:40,042
I say: "What's that smell?"
-That's not what you say.

328
00:32:40,240 --> 00:32:42,641
It is, because then she'll say:
"That's my perfume."

329
00:32:42,840 --> 00:32:45,446
And then I'll say: "Mmm, nice..."

330
00:32:45,640 --> 00:32:48,166
Or: "Pooh, horrible."
That depends on her perfume.

331
00:32:48,360 --> 00:32:50,283
You say: "Mmm, nice"! Understood?

332
00:32:50,840 --> 00:32:52,569
Even if she smells of sweat,
or chips?

333
00:32:52,760 --> 00:32:54,410
She doesn't smell of chips.

334
00:32:54,600 --> 00:32:57,922
But she's working-class,
and they smell of chips.

335
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:00,729
Did you impart this gem?

336
00:33:00,920 --> 00:33:04,288
Lots of poor people smell of chips.
Haven't you ever noticed?

337
00:33:04,480 --> 00:33:06,244
She doesn't come from
a working-class family...

338
00:33:06,440 --> 00:33:09,330
...so she doesn't smell of chips.

339
00:33:09,520 --> 00:33:12,603
She smells nice! You say: "Mmm, nice",
or "Mmm, lovely"...

340
00:33:12,800 --> 00:33:15,485
...and not: "Pooh, horrible'.
"Mmm, lovely"!

341
00:33:15,680 --> 00:33:19,685
And Dove will echo that
with a friendly look. Yes?

342
00:33:19,880 --> 00:33:22,804
Then she says: "Thank you".

343
00:33:23,040 --> 00:33:26,408
A brief silence is in order,
and then you continue.

344
00:33:26,600 --> 00:33:29,126
I ask: "Would you care for a drink?"

345
00:33:29,480 --> 00:33:31,323
And then she will of course ask me
"What have you got?"

346
00:33:31,520 --> 00:33:32,043
Dove?

347
00:33:33,400 --> 00:33:39,123
Beer, wine, coffee, tea,
sherry, whisky...

348
00:33:39,320 --> 00:33:40,924
...various liqeurs and gin.

349
00:33:41,120 --> 00:33:44,806
And mineral water?
Because she's a tee-totaller.

350
00:33:45,320 --> 00:33:47,163
And mineral water.

351
00:33:47,920 --> 00:33:51,049
While Dove's pouring the drinks,
you staﬂ breaking the ice.

352
00:33:51,320 --> 00:33:52,446
Something about the Iron Curtain?

353
00:33:52,640 --> 00:33:55,007
I don't want to hear the word
Iron Curtain!

354
00:33:55,640 --> 00:33:58,246
Why not? It's something
Abel knows a lot about.

355
00:33:58,440 --> 00:34:01,444
Tonight it's ordinary conversations!

356
00:34:02,480 --> 00:34:04,289
Have you got any brothers
or sisters?

357
00:34:04,480 --> 00:34:06,005
That's it, that's a good question.

358
00:34:06,200 --> 00:34:08,521
Has she got any, then?
-I don't believe she has.

359
00:34:08,720 --> 00:34:12,088
Then it isn't a good question at all.

360
00:34:12,480 --> 00:34:16,565
I ask, why do you do acting,
anyway?

361
00:34:16,880 --> 00:34:18,245
Yes, you ask that.

362
00:34:18,440 --> 00:34:19,726
A conversation develops.

363
00:34:19,920 --> 00:34:22,844
It had better. I want
a spontaneous evening.

364
00:34:26,240 --> 00:34:29,050
One more thing. I want
this understood:

365
00:34:29,400 --> 00:34:32,609
This evening, if I touch
my nose like this...

366
00:34:32,800 --> 00:34:38,125
...then Dove puts a record on
and you ask her to dance.

367
00:34:38,560 --> 00:34:41,689
And if I run my right hand through
my hair, like this...

368
00:34:42,320 --> 00:34:44,084
...then Dove tells that story.

369
00:34:44,280 --> 00:34:45,327
Which story?

370
00:34:45,520 --> 00:34:47,921
The one about the llama in the zoo.

371
00:34:48,120 --> 00:34:51,488
We already know that story.
-We don't already know that story!

372
00:35:20,960 --> 00:35:23,611
Christine, this is Dove, my wife.

373
00:35:24,720 --> 00:35:26,927
Pleased to meet you.

374
00:35:27,160 --> 00:35:30,801
And that is Abel, my son.

375
00:35:39,240 --> 00:35:42,961
Something to drink?
-A glass of gin, perhaps?

376
00:35:43,480 --> 00:35:46,131
Victor must have told you.

377
00:35:46,760 --> 00:35:50,082
Yes... Let's go and sit down.

378
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:06,082
What a nice plant.

379
00:37:09,800 --> 00:37:11,882
It looks like a tomato plant.

380
00:37:14,800 --> 00:37:16,404
I'm mad about tomatoes.

381
00:37:19,200 --> 00:37:21,521
But I'm not allowed to eat them.

382
00:37:26,120 --> 00:37:28,327
She's mad about tomatoes.

383
00:37:29,240 --> 00:37:30,924
Would you like a tomato?

384
00:37:32,440 --> 00:37:34,522
I'm not allowed to eat them.

385
00:38:05,800 --> 00:38:08,007
Why not?

386
00:38:10,760 --> 00:38:12,330
Aren't you allowed
to eat tomatoes?

387
00:38:13,560 --> 00:38:16,131
Tomatoes belong to the
nightshade family.

388
00:38:16,320 --> 00:38:18,687
Everything which belongs
to that family is bad for you.

389
00:38:19,320 --> 00:38:21,209
Potatoes, for instance, as well.

390
00:38:21,400 --> 00:38:23,562
Potatoes?
-Yes.

391
00:38:32,120 --> 00:38:35,090
Why do you do acting?
-Me?

392
00:38:37,280 --> 00:38:39,806
I like climbing into
someone else's skin.

393
00:38:41,960 --> 00:38:45,043
Can you play things
as well as people?

394
00:38:45,840 --> 00:38:46,523
Things?

395
00:38:48,360 --> 00:38:53,924
Could you also climb
into the skin of... a potato?

396
00:38:55,480 --> 00:38:58,211
No, no, I can't do that.

397
00:38:59,400 --> 00:39:01,880
I think you'd make
a very good potato.

398
00:39:32,520 --> 00:39:34,966
Why do you keep touching
your nose?

399
00:41:21,720 --> 00:41:23,563
And now for some more talking.

400
00:41:35,080 --> 00:41:38,562
Isn't it about time
for a nice salty herring?

401
00:41:51,560 --> 00:41:52,686
Not for me, thanks.

402
00:41:52,960 --> 00:41:54,325
Don't you like herring?

403
00:41:54,520 --> 00:41:56,966
Rather! But I'm not allowed
to have it.

404
00:41:58,040 --> 00:42:00,122
Is herring also a member
of the nightshade family?

405
00:42:00,320 --> 00:42:02,402
No, that's impossible.
- Well then.

406
00:42:03,280 --> 00:42:05,487
Herring is bad for your heart.

407
00:43:32,760 --> 00:43:33,727
Dove!

408
00:43:33,920 --> 00:43:36,890
Don't be absurd. Let me go.

409
00:43:37,360 --> 00:43:39,681
Leave them for a while...

410
00:43:40,080 --> 00:43:42,765
Ridiculous, it'll come to nothing.

411
00:43:43,640 --> 00:43:48,407
...the children are too small
to work in the factory...

412
00:43:48,600 --> 00:43:51,922
...so they can't afford
to clothe them.

413
00:43:53,520 --> 00:43:56,490
But their mothers wear
long woollen skids.

414
00:43:56,680 --> 00:43:58,284
And when the children go outside...

415
00:43:58,480 --> 00:44:01,006
...they walk naked under their
mother's skids.

416
00:44:01,760 --> 00:44:04,206
But the cold gives them
pneumonia.

417
00:44:04,400 --> 00:44:07,483
They often die by the walkside.
-Time for a top-up, Dove.

418
00:44:12,480 --> 00:44:14,084
No, thank you.

419
00:44:14,280 --> 00:44:17,090
Fish has to swim, you know.
- But I haven't eaten any fish.

420
00:44:41,320 --> 00:44:44,403
Come on, you don't think
I feel like telling...

421
00:44:44,600 --> 00:44:46,887
...the story about the llama now?
-What are you talking about?

422
00:45:26,240 --> 00:45:29,767
You're out of step, girlie.
You've got to follow Abel.

423
00:45:45,200 --> 00:45:47,441
I can't dance like this, you know.

424
00:46:23,320 --> 00:46:24,731
No.

425
00:46:28,560 --> 00:46:30,688
You're having an affair.

426
00:46:32,920 --> 00:46:34,763
Night-night.

427
00:46:36,560 --> 00:46:38,801
You're having an affair.

428
00:46:39,920 --> 00:46:43,481
You're having an affair with
a beautiful, young, fertile woman.

429
00:46:43,680 --> 00:46:44,647
I can feel it!

430
00:46:44,840 --> 00:46:46,444
Stop it!

431
00:46:57,720 --> 00:47:00,371
Say that you're having an affair.

432
00:47:00,600 --> 00:47:02,648
I'm not having an affair.

433
00:47:04,800 --> 00:47:07,121
Why can't an evening
like this evening...

434
00:47:07,320 --> 00:47:09,641
"because you know how
to fix things, eh...

435
00:47:09,840 --> 00:47:12,081
...be conducted normally?

436
00:47:14,320 --> 00:47:16,607
Why isn't life normal?

437
00:47:25,840 --> 00:47:27,683
Vickie...

438
00:47:30,360 --> 00:47:32,089
Vickie...

439
00:47:37,080 --> 00:47:41,483
Come now, Christine, your lines.
"I'm not used to" etcetera.

440
00:47:45,240 --> 00:47:47,641
Yes, why not?

441
00:47:47,960 --> 00:47:50,088
Very good, carry on.

442
00:48:44,320 --> 00:48:46,209
Are you my little amateur?

443
00:48:46,400 --> 00:48:48,721
Is that surprising?
With this row going on?

444
00:48:49,080 --> 00:48:51,526
Perhaps we should make it
more stimulating.

445
00:48:51,840 --> 00:48:55,049
I did it with a general once,
that was exciting.

446
00:48:55,240 --> 00:48:57,447
Have you had an affair
with a general?

447
00:48:57,640 --> 00:49:02,487
He wasn't a general.
He just dressed up as a general.

448
00:49:02,680 --> 00:49:05,160
Oh, you mean I should, er...

449
00:49:11,120 --> 00:49:13,441
You could be something else.

450
00:50:16,240 --> 00:50:19,005
What on earth are you wearing?
- A polo-neck.

451
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:22,844
I thought you couldn't stand
polo-necks?

452
00:51:41,120 --> 00:51:43,122
Give it here, woman.

453
00:51:46,880 --> 00:51:49,121
Oh, Victor!

454
00:51:55,880 --> 00:51:59,202
What a lovely red mark!

455
00:52:00,400 --> 00:52:04,644
I'm glad that we're all getting
with each other again.

456
00:52:05,440 --> 00:52:08,250
The last time that happened
was, I believe, in 1962.

457
00:52:08,640 --> 00:52:10,404
Give over, Victor.

458
00:52:10,840 --> 00:52:15,687
To show you I'm not a bad sod,
I've decided...

459
00:52:18,800 --> 00:52:20,643
...tomorrow, I'm going to buy
a television.

460
00:52:38,120 --> 00:52:42,170
Where is that television?
Where's the bloody thing? Damn it!

461
00:52:42,360 --> 00:52:46,809
Please, Vicky, let's talk this over.
- Talk, my foot!

462
00:52:47,280 --> 00:52:50,443
We wanted to surprise you.
- I call it deceit.

463
00:52:55,800 --> 00:52:58,041
Out of this house!

464
00:53:11,680 --> 00:53:13,409
Bloody hell, open this door!

465
00:53:14,800 --> 00:53:16,529
Shut your trap!

466
00:53:19,560 --> 00:53:21,961
I'm going to do you
a mischief!

467
00:53:48,360 --> 00:53:54,242
Where are you going?
- I'm leaving. It stinks here.

468
00:54:59,560 --> 00:55:01,608
Move over a bit.
You're in the way.

469
00:55:12,680 --> 00:55:16,810
Victor, Victor.

470
00:55:18,640 --> 00:55:21,484
Please, Victor, please.
-Give him a coat.

471
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:26,050
Victor, please, please, I beg you!

472
00:55:26,240 --> 00:55:28,481
Too late!
Give him his coat, I said!

473
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:36,923
You're not really going
to throw me out, are you?

474
00:55:37,120 --> 00:55:39,521
Oh no? What kind of a mug
do you think I am?

475
00:55:41,640 --> 00:55:43,404
Give your mother a kiss.

476
01:00:13,600 --> 01:00:14,965
Stop there.

477
01:00:15,560 --> 01:00:16,607
Where?
- There.

478
01:00:18,520 --> 01:00:20,727
What would he be doing
in a lunchroom?

479
01:00:23,160 --> 01:00:24,685
Stop!

480
01:00:54,560 --> 01:00:56,608
Where are you going?

481
01:00:58,280 --> 01:00:59,611
Let's make a date.

482
01:01:05,160 --> 01:01:07,049
What are you doing?
- Can't I look for him?

483
01:01:07,240 --> 01:01:09,402
Can I take your arm?
- Why?

484
01:01:09,600 --> 01:01:11,648
Well, all the men around here.

485
01:01:13,440 --> 01:01:15,761
I can't see any men.
-No, but they can see us.

486
01:01:15,960 --> 01:01:19,043
Now they'll think I'm with you.

487
01:01:27,920 --> 01:01:30,082
It was your first time?

488
01:01:35,680 --> 01:01:37,682
It was your first time.

489
01:01:41,280 --> 01:01:45,330
It doesn't matter.
You're just a late developer.

490
01:03:03,880 --> 01:03:05,769
